recalls.Summary: Drake Automotive Group, LLC (Drake) is recalling certain Scott Drake left and right wheel spindles, part numbers C5ZZ-3106-L, C5ZZ-3105-R, C70Z-3106-L, C70Z-3105-R sold for use on 1965-1966 Ford Mustang V8s and 1967-1969 Ford Mustangs (all vehicles with drums).  The spindle may fail resulting in the wheel and tire detaching from the vehicle's steering system.
recalls.Consequence: Spindle failure can cause a loss of steering control, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Drake Automotive Group, LLC will notify owners and will replace all of the recalled units, free of charge.  The recall began March 17, 2019.  Owners may contact Drake automotive at 1-800-999-0289.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

POSSIBLE STEERING WHEEL SPOKE BREAKAGE INVOLVING ONE OR MORE OF THE METAL INSERTS WITHIN THE PLASTIC SPOKE.  UNDER EXTENDED USAGE THE SEPARATION MAY EXTEND TO ALL THREE METAL INSERTS AND EVENTUALLY AFFECT STEERING CONTROL.  (INSPECT AND REPLACE STEERING WHEELS AS NECESSARY.)

POSSIBILITY THAT THE STEERING WHEEL RETAINING NUT WAS IMPROPERLY INSTALLED.  THIS COULD ALLOW THE STEERING WHEEL TO BECOME LOOSE OR DISCONNECTED.  (INSPECT AND SECURE STEERING WHEEL RETAINING NUT AS REQUIRED.)

THIS CAUSES OBJECTIONABLE NOISE, AND IF DONE REPEATEDLY, WILL SCUFF THE OUTER EDGE OF THE TIRE.  (REWORK FRONT FENDER WHEEL OPENING FLANGE AND REMOVE MOULDINGS TO ELIMINATE POSSIBLE INTERFERENCE.)

complaints.summary: FORD, 1967 MUSTANG,  SIX CYL AUTO TRANS.  WHILE I WAS STOPPED FOR A LIGHT,  THE CARBURETOR RETURN SPRING LET GO.  LUCKY FOR ME, I HAD MY FOOT ON THE BRAKE AND OFF THE GAS PEDAL AS I WAS STILL IN DRIVE.  I HEARD THE SPRING BOUNCE OFF THE FAN AND THE ENGINE SPEED UP. I SHUT OFF THE ENGINE, TOOK THE  SHIFT OUT OF DRIVE AND COASTED TO THE CURB.. I COULD NOT FIND ANY PART OF THE SPRING OR ANCHOR POINT.    I TOOK A SPRING OUT FROM UNDER THE PASSENGER SEAT AND USED THAT ARRANGEMENT FOR A NUMBER OF YEARS.  I STILL HAVE THE CAR IN THE GARAGE BUT HAVE NOT USED IT FOR ABOUT 30 YEARS.    AT THE TIME THERE WERE A NUMBER OF INCIDENTS WHERE THESE MUSTANGS SPED UP OUT OF CONTROL, WITH SERIOUS CONSEQUENCES.    FORD WOULD NOT OWN UP TO THE PROBLEM.  I HAD GONE TO FORD ASKING FOR REPLACEMENT PARTS, BUT NO RESPONSE.  I HAD WRITTEN TO NTSB A NUMBER OF YEARS AGO, BUT NO RESPONSE THERE EITHER.    STATUE OF LIMITATIONS HAS MOST LIKELY RUN OUT FOR REPARATIONS TO THE ACCIDENT VICTIMS.    OF COURSE THE PROBLEM WAS EVENTUALLY RECOGNIZED WITHOUT HONOR TO THE VICTIMS AND THE TENSION SPRINGS REPLACED BY A SERIES OF COMPRESSION SPRINGS ON LATER MODELS THEREAFTER.    NEVER HAVE RECEIVED A RECALL NOTICE BY FORD. *TR

issues.title: Power Steering Box Leakage
issues.description: The original power steering gear boxes commonly develop leaks at the input shaft and sector shaft seals, causing power steering fluid to leak onto the ground and potentially causing steering difficulties.
symptoms: Power steering fluid puddles under car
issues.fix_description: Replace power steering gear box seals or rebuild/replace entire steering box
issues.prevention: Regular power steering fluid changes and checking fluid levels

issues.title: C4 Automatic Transmission Overheating
issues.description: The C4 automatic transmission used in these years is prone to overheating, especially during heavy use, leading to transmission failure and burned fluid.
issues.fix_description: Install transmission cooler, rebuild transmission with updated parts, or replace transmission
issues.prevention: Regular transmission fluid changes, install auxiliary cooler, avoid heavy towing

issues.title: Upper Control Arm Bushing Failure
issues.description: The rubber bushings in the upper control arms deteriorate over time, causing poor handling, tire wear, and potential safety issues due to loss of proper wheel alignment.
issues.fix_description: Replace upper control arm bushings with new rubber or polyurethane bushings
issues.prevention: Regular inspection of suspension components, avoid harsh driving conditions

issues.title: Carburetor Float Sticking
issues.description: The Autolite 2100 and 4100 series carburetors commonly experience float sticking, causing fuel flooding or starvation issues that affect engine performance.
issues.fix_description: Clean or rebuild carburetor, replace float and needle valve assembly
issues.prevention: Use quality fuel, regular carburetor maintenance, fuel system cleaning

issues.title: Rear Axle Bearing Failure
issues.description: The rear axle bearings in the 8.5 and 9-inch rear ends are prone to failure, especially in high-performance applications, causing noise and potential axle damage.
issues.fix_description: Replace rear axle bearings and seals, inspect axle shafts for damage
issues.prevention: Regular differential fluid changes, avoid hard acceleration from standstill

issues.title: Ignition Points and Condenser Failure
issues.description: The points-based ignition system requires frequent maintenance as points wear out and condensers fail, causing misfiring and poor engine performance.
issues.fix_description: Replace points, condenser, and rotor; adjust point gap and timing
issues.prevention: Regular tune-ups every 6,000-10,000 miles, quality ignition components

issues.title: Brake Master Cylinder Leakage
issues.description: Single-circuit master cylinders used in these years are prone to internal seal failure, causing brake fluid loss and potential complete brake failure.
issues.fix_description: Replace or rebuild master cylinder, flush brake system, upgrade to dual-circuit system
issues.prevention: Regular brake fluid changes, inspect brake system regularly

issues.title: Fuel Tank Vapor Lock
issues.description: The fuel system design is susceptible to vapor lock in hot weather, where fuel vaporizes in the lines causing fuel starvation and stalling.
issues.fix_description: Install heat shields on fuel lines, relocate fuel lines away from heat sources, install electric fuel pump
issues.prevention: Use proper octane fuel, avoid letting tank get too low in hot weather

issues.title: Door Hinge Pin Wear
issues.description: Door hinge pins and bushings wear out over time, causing doors to sag and not align properly, making closing difficult and creating gaps.
issues.fix_description: Replace door hinge pins and bushings, adjust door alignment
issues.prevention: Regular lubrication of door hinges, gentle door operation

issues.title: Heater Core Leakage
issues.description: The original heater cores are prone to developing leaks due to age and corrosion, causing coolant loss and fogged windows inside the vehicle.
issues.fix_description: Replace heater core, flush cooling system, check heater hoses
issues.prevention: Regular cooling system maintenance, use proper coolant mixture

issues.title: Generator/Alternator Failure
issues.description: Early 1967 models with generators and 1968 models with early alternators experience charging system failures, leading to battery drain and electrical problems.
issues.fix_description: Rebuild or replace generator/alternator, check charging system wiring
issues.prevention: Regular electrical system inspection, avoid overloading electrical system

issues.title: Exhaust Manifold Cracking
issues.description: Cast iron exhaust manifolds, especially on high-performance engines, are prone to cracking due to heat cycling, causing exhaust leaks and performance loss.
issues.fix_description: Replace cracked exhaust manifolds, upgrade to headers if desired
issues.prevention: Allow engine to warm up gradually, avoid rapid temperature changes

editorial.tagline: The pony that started the muscle car revolution
editorial.hero_blurb: The '67-'68 Mustang Fastback represents the sweet spot where the original pony car formula reached its perfect balance. With the 289 Hi-Po V8 under the hood, this is pure American muscle wrapped in timeless fastback styling that still turns heads today.
editorial.essence: This generation perfected the Mustang's DNA - accessible performance, stunning looks, and that unmistakable American V8 growl. The fastback silhouette became an icon, while the 289 Hi-Po delivered genuine muscle car thrills without the intimidation factor of big-block monsters.
editorial.heritage: Born from the original 1964Â½ Mustang revolution, the '67-'68 models received their first major redesign with more aggressive styling and increased performance. These years bridged the gap between the original pony car concept and the full-blown muscle car era that followed.
editorial.design_philosophy: Ford's designers aimed to evolve the Mustang from cute to aggressive while maintaining its youthful appeal. The fastback roofline added drama and performance credibility, while subtle body changes gave it more presence without losing the original's charm.
editorial.motorsport_history: The 289 Hi-Po Fastback dominated SCCA Trans-Am racing and proved itself in drag strips across America. Its balanced weight distribution and nimble handling made it a favorite among weekend warriors and professional racers alike.
editorial.engine_character: The 289 Hi-Po is a high-revving jewel that loves to be wound out. It builds power progressively with a eager, willing character that begs you to explore every RPM. This isn't brute force - it's refined American muscle.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 4-speed manual shifts with mechanical precision and short, deliberate throws. Each gear change feels purposeful and engaging, connecting driver to drivetrain in that visceral way that made these cars legendary.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Surprisingly balanced for its era, with a front-heavy bias that's manageable and predictable. The live rear axle provides classic muscle car character while the relatively light weight keeps things playful rather than overwhelming.
editorial.steering_feel: Manual steering offers pure, unfiltered feedback with moderate effort at parking speeds. On the road, it's communicative and direct, letting you feel exactly what the front wheels are doing through every corner.
editorial.brake_confidence: Front disc brakes provide adequate stopping power for the era, though they require more planning than modern systems. The pedal feel is progressive and predictable, building confidence through consistency rather than outright power.
editorial.sound_signature: The 289 Hi-Po produces a distinctive high-pitched V8 growl that's more sophisticated than raw. It revs freely with a mechanical intensity that builds to an intoxicating wail at redline - pure automotive music.
editorial.ideal_owner: Perfect for the driving enthusiast who appreciates classic American muscle with manners. Ideal for someone who wants genuine vintage performance without the complexity or intimidation of big-block power.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Those seeking modern convenience, air conditioning comfort, or maximum straight-line performance should look elsewhere. This isn't a boulevard cruiser - it's a driver's car that demands engagement.
editorial.buyers_summary: Look for solid, rust-free examples with numbers-matching drivetrains and original sheet metal. The 289 Hi-Po is reliable and parts are available, but genuine Hi-Po engines command premium prices and should be verified carefully.

expertReviews.title: Mustang GT Fastback Review 2025 - The Icon Reimagined ... by Webby On Cars
pros: Still available with V8 engine (345kW, 550Nm)
Updated exterior design with new headlights and improved rear styling
Modern infotainment with wireless Apple CarPlay/Android Auto
Customizable digital dash with retro Mustang themes
Active exhaust system with multiple sound modes
Comfortable heated and cooled seats
Great engine sound and driving experience
cons: No front parking sensors or cameras
Wireless charging deleted on 2025 models
Cannot combine appearance pack with MagneRide suspension
Very limited rear seat space
Traditional handbrake on wrong side for Australia
Color options being frequently changed/deleted
expertReviews.verdict: The 2024 Mustang GT receives significant updates including refreshed styling, modern infotainment, and customizable digital displays while retaining the beloved 5.0L V8. Despite some packaging limitations and option restrictions, it successfully balances modern technology with classic muscle car character. May be one of the last V8 Mustangs available.

expertReviews.title: 2025 Ford Mustang GT Review | One MAJOR Change!
pros: 480 horsepower naturally aspirated Coyote V8
Quick paddle shifter response
Excellent braking performance (99ft 60-0)
Great steering feel especially in sport mode
Distinct exhaust sound
Better visibility than competitors like Camaro
Mustang community and culture
cons: Substantial price increase of $4,065 from previous year
Rear seats unusable for adults (29 inches legroom)
Limited cargo space
Firmer ride quality
expertReviews.verdict: The 2025 Mustang GT retains the beloved naturally aspirated V8 with 480hp while adding modern features. Despite a significant price bump, it delivers excellent performance with quick acceleration, outstanding braking, and engaging driving dynamics. The paddle shifters are responsive and the exhaust note is distinctive. However, practicality suffers with unusable rear seats and the price increase may concern buyers. Overall maintains the classic Mustang character while modernizing the experience.

expertReviews.title: 2025 Ford Mustang GT Fastback Auto Review | Why the V8 Auto Outsells the Manual
pros: Excellent Coyote V8 engine with fat mid-range and sings to 7000+ RPM
Refined handling with flat and accurate cornering
Confidence inspiring Brembo brakes
More modern interior tech with 13.2-inch touchscreen and configurable instrument panel
Better fuel economy than manual transmission
Improved safety equipment including blind spot monitoring
cons: Price over $90,000 including on-road costs
10-speed auto transmission is fumbly in sport mode and not mechanically well connected
Pretty sharp and jolting ride quality
Dashboard rattles and gurgling sounds from sound enhancer
Poor rear seat space - treat as luggage space only
Limited camera and sensor assistance for such a large car
expertReviews.verdict: The 2025 Mustang GT Fastback Auto is a step forward from the previous generation with excellent V8 performance, refined handling, and modern tech, but comes at a premium price. While the auto transmission dilutes the experience slightly compared to manual, it's still compelling. The harsh ride and build quality issues are concerning, but as the last semi-attainable V8 rear-wheel drive sports car under $100k, it remains a worthwhile experience despite the big bucks required.

expertReviews.title: The Best Mustang Ever? (Ford Mustang 2025 Long-Term ...)
pros: Best driving Mustang so far
Easy manual transmission to drive
Excellent build quality - best built American car in years
Impressive traction and suspension handling
Great sound and exhaust note
Wireless Apple CarPlay works 99% of the time
Much better fit and finish than previous generation
Tractable engine with good low-end torque
Looks fantastic - edgier and sleeker than predecessor
cons: $5,000 price increase across lineup
Auto stop-start can be annoying
Some interior buttons feel flimsy
Cold tire traction still prone to oversteer
Costs tens of thousands more than it used to
expertReviews.verdict: This 7th generation Mustang GT Fastback manual represents a significant improvement over its predecessor, feeling like a genuinely different generation despite sharing the same platform. The reviewer praises it as potentially the best Mustang of all time, with exceptional build quality, excellent manual transmission feel, impressive handling, and strong everyday usability. At $83,990 before options, it's expensive but offers substantial value as essentially the last of its kind in the muscle car segment.

expertReviews.title: Seven Months In Ford's V8 Weapon (Ford Mustang 2026 Long ...)
pros: Outstanding 5.0L V8 sound with active bimodal exhaust
Excellent handling with Magnaride dampers and limited slip diff
Large 400L boot with folding rear seats
Strong tractability - can pull effortlessly from 1000 RPM
Aggressive muscular styling with great road presence
cons: 10-speed automatic transmission is unsatisfying compared to manual
Poor door storage with no practical cup holders or storage spaces
B&O stereo sounds thin despite 12 speakers
Poor fuel economy - 23L/100km city, 15.3L/100km average
Apple CarPlay blocks access to features when driving
expertReviews.verdict: After 7 months testing both manual and automatic versions, the reviewer strongly prefers the manual GT over the automatic. The Mustang GT delivers authentic V8 muscle car experience with excellent handling dynamics that rival European sports cars. Despite practical issues like poor storage and fuel economy, it's praised as the perfect modern interpretation of Australian muscle car heritage. Manual transmission is essential for the full experience.

expertReviews.title: Driving a 1968 Ford Mustang GT Fastback by Revology Cars
pros: Modern technology underneath vintage exterior
Excellent build quality with tight body panel tolerances
460-710 horsepower engine options with modern refinement
Superior handling compared to original Mustang
Modern conveniences like LED lighting, touchscreen, Apple CarPlay
Quiet operation with reduced wind and drivetrain noise
Custom-built from scratch with modern engineering
Four-wheel Wilwood disc brakes with 17-inch wheels
Power rack and pinion steering
Double wishbone suspension
cons: Not an original Ford product
Requires relearning driving habits due to modern capabilities
Still has aerodynamics of original 1960s design
expertReviews.verdict: The Revology Cars 1968 Mustang GT Fastback successfully combines vintage aesthetics with modern performance and convenience. Built from scratch rather than restored, it offers the visual appeal of a classic muscle car with the reliability, handling, and refinement of a contemporary vehicle. With options ranging from 460 to 710 horsepower and extensive customization available, it delivers modern driving dynamics while maintaining authentic vintage appearance.
